\begin{frame}{Nash's Existence Theorem }

\begin{block}{Theorem (Nash's Existence Theorem)}
Any n-player normal-form game with finite strategy sets $S_i$ for all players has a (Nash) equilibrium in either pure or mixed strategies.
    
\end{block}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The Nash equilibrium solution concept is powerful because it exists for most games. 
        \item Nash equilibrium leads to more refined predictions than strictly dominant strategy equilibrium and iterated-elimination equilibrium. 
        \item Nash equilibrium is widely used by game theorists. 
        
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Nash's Existence Theorem }
\begin{block}{Definition}
A pure-strategy profile $s^*\in S$ is a Nash equilibrium if and only if it is a fixed point of the collection  of best-response correspondences, $s^*\in BR(s^*)$. 

\end{block}

 \begin{block}{Definition}
A mixed-strategy profile $\sigma^*\in \Delta S$ is a Nash equilibrium if and only if it is a fixed point of the collection  of best-response correspondences, $\sigma ^*\in BR(\sigma^*)$. 

\end{block}   

If it is possible to prove that a fixed point exists, then it implies that a Nash equilibrium exists.
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Brouwer's Fixed-Point Theorem}
\begin{block}{Theorem}
If $f(x)$ is a continuous function from the domain $[0,1]$ to itself then there exists at least one fixed point, i.e., a value $x^*\in [0,1]$ such that $f(x^*)=x^*$. 

\end{block}
    The idea is that if $f(x)$ takes values from the interval $[0,1]$ and generates results from the same interval $[0,1]$, then there has to be a value $x^*$ in the interval for which the function $f(x)$ gives back the same value. 
    
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Kakutani's Fixed-Point Theorem }
\begin{block}{Theorem (Kakutani's Fixed-Point Theorem)}
A best response correspondence $BR: \Delta S \rightarrow \Delta S$ has a fixed point $\sigma \in BR(\sigma) $ if four conditions are satisfied:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item $\Delta S$ is a non-empty, compact, and convex subset of $\mathcal{R}^n$;
    \item $BR(\sigma)$ is non-empty for all $\sigma$;
    \item $BR(\sigma)$ is convex for all $\sigma$; 
    \item $BR$ has a closed graph.
\end{enumerate}
\end{block}
\begin{itemize}
    \item  Nash equilibrium uses Kakutani's fixed-point theorem  on best-response correspondences to show that it has a fixed point.
    \item All four conditions of Kakutani's fixed-point theorem are satisfied for any $2\times 2$ game. Therefore, any $2\times 2$ game has at least one Nash equilibrium.
    
\end{itemize}

    
\end{frame}
\begin{frame}{Studying Nash Equilibrium Experimentally}
    \begin{itemize}
        \item The theory of strategic games lends itself to experimental study: arranging for subjects to play games and observing their choices is relatively straightforward.
         \item The theory of Nash equilibrium, as we have seen, has two components: the players act in accordance with the theory of rational choice, given their beliefs about the other playersâ€™ actions, and these beliefs are correct.
        \item Behavioral studies however, are inconclusive regarding Nash equilibrium.
       
    \end{itemize}
\end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Never Best Response}
  \begin{block}{Definition}
  A strategy $s_i\in S_i$ is \textbf{never best response} if there is no strategy $s_{-i}\in S_{-i}$ such that $s_i\in BR(s_{-i})$.
  \end{block}  
  \begin{itemize}
      \item Players can never justify playing a never best response. 
      \item A rational player should not play a strategy that is a never best response. 
      \item This is a common knowledge: We can eliminate strategies that are never best response. 
  \end{itemize}
  \end{frame}

\begin{frame}{Never Best Response}

 \begin{table}[]
\centering

%\label{mtel}
\begin{tabular}{clcc}
\multicolumn{1}{l}{}      & \multicolumn{1}{c}{}               & \multicolumn{2}{c}{Player 2}                                   \\
\multirow{4}{*}{Player 1} &                                    & \multicolumn{1}{l}{$Left$} & \multicolumn{1}{l}{$Right$}  \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{$Up$} & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1,1}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}
                          \\ \cline{3-4} 
                          & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{$Middle$}       &
                          \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}
                           \\ \cline{3-4}
                            
                           & \multicolumn{1}{l|}{$Down$}       &
                          \multicolumn{1}{c|}{0,0}        & \multicolumn{1}{c|}{1, 1}
                           \\ \cline{3-4}
\end{tabular}
\end{table}
\bigskip 
Middle is never best response:
\begin{itemize}
    \item If player 1 believes player 2 will play Left, then $BR(Left)=\{Up\}$.
    \item If player 1 believes player 2 will play Right, then $BR(Right)=\{Down\}$.
\end{itemize}
We should never observe player 1 playing Middle.
\end{frame}


\begin{frame}{Summary}
\begin{itemize}
    \item In zero-sum games, there is no pure-strategy Nash equilibrium, however, mixed-strategy Nash equilibrium exists.
    \item We saw examples where pure-strategy Nash equilibrium did not exist but mixed-strategy existed, and also an example, where mixed-strategy did not exist but pure-strategy existed. 
    \item In general, Nash proved that for finite games there will be at least one Nash equilibrium.
\end{itemize}
    
\end{frame}





